This is the OCPL Coq development. It's a fork of the [Iris Coq
development](http://iris-project.org) (started a bit before the Iris
3.0 release) supporting the paper

	Robust and Compositional Verification of Object Capability
	Patterns

The development depends only on Coq, and we've tested it under Coq
8.9.1 (July 2019). After installing Coq (e.g., [via
Opam](https://coq.inria.fr/opam-using.html), a simple `make -jN`,
where `N` is the number of cores you have, should compile everything.
The file `./vendor/iris-coq/README.md` contains (outdated build instructions and)
a brief tour of the version of Iris we started with.

To develop OCPL, we changed Iris' sample program logic to support the
distinction between progressive and non-progressive weakest
preconditions and Iris' sample heap language to support assertion
expressions (i.e., so we could state robust safety). We call the
modified heap language HLA.

Our work on progress bits appears in ./vendor/iris-coq/theories/program_logic/; in
particular ./vendor/iris-coq/theories/program_logic/weakestpre.v. For presentation
purposes, we use Hoare triples in the paper (and, in the Coq
development, to state many of our lemmas), but proofs always work at
the more fundamental level of weakest preconditions.

Our work on HLA appears in ./vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/. The most interesting
bits are:

	vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/lang.v
		language definition

	vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/on_val.v
		the predicate transformer called `lift` in the paper

	vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/heap.v
		heap resources (e.g., the points-to assertion), the
		invariant supporting robust safety, and rules for
		working with the heap

		We suppress this (pervasive) heap invariant in the
		paper. It shows up as [heap_ctx] when verifying code.

		Our heap interface is a bit richer than what we
		describe in the paper; for example, the points-to
		assertion supports fractional permissions and we have
		a rule [heap_mark_low] for converting a high-integrity
		location containing a low value into a low-integrity
		location.

	vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/substitution.v
	vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/robust_safety.v
		the fundamental theorem of logical relations and the
		"internal" version of robust safety (generalizing the
		meta-level robust safety theorem from contexts with no
		locations to contexts with only low locations)

	vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/adequacy.v
		metatheory, including the robust safety theorem stated
		in the paper

As far as examples go, you will find general object capability
patterns (OCPs) in

	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/lib/sealing.v
	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/lib/caretaker.v
	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/lib/membrane.v

and derived OCPs and client programs in

	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/tests/sealing.v
	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/tests/caretaker.v
	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/tests/membrane.v
	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/tests/readonly.v

(These are the files in which we apply the robust safety theorem to
whole programs and ask Coq to confirm that the result is axiom-free.)

The paper mentions a few libraries:

	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/lib/lock.v
	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/lib/spin_lock.v
	./vendor/iris-coq/theories/heap_lang/lib/maps.v
